IAM is the security backbone for AWS data pipelines. Each service (Glue, EMR, Lambda, ECS) needs a role with least-privilege policies.

Pattern: role + policy attachment:
```hcl
# IAM role for Glue jobs
resource "aws_iam_role" "glue_role" {
  name = "glue-etl-role"
  assume_role_policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [{
      Effect    = "Allow"
      Principal = { Service = "glue.amazonaws.com" }
      Action    = "sts:AssumeRole"
    }]
  })
}

# Attach managed policy
resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "glue_service" {
  role       = aws_iam_role.glue_role.name
  policy_arn = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AWSGlueServiceRole"
}

# Custom inline policy for S3 data lake access
resource "aws_iam_role_policy" "glue_s3_access" {
  name = "glue-s3-data-lake"
  role = aws_iam_role.glue_role.id
  policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [{
      Effect   = "Allow"
      Action   = ["s3:GetObject", "s3:PutObject", "s3:DeleteObject"]
      Resource = "${aws_s3_bucket.data_lake.arn}/*"
    }]
  })
}
```

Best practices:
- Use least-privilege: only grant what the service needs
- Prefer managed policies for standard services, inline for custom S3/resource access
- Never use AdministratorAccess for pipeline roles
- Use resource ARNs (not '*') wherever possible
